text.Taxonomy and naming:
The species was first formally described in 1899 by Spencer Le Marchant Moore who gave it the name Pholidia interstans. The description was published in Journal of the Linnean Society, Botany. In 1904, Ludwig Diels and Ernst Georg Pritzel changed the name to Eremophila interstans. When Moore described the species, he noted that it seemed to be intermediate between the two genera Eremophila and Pholidia recognised at the time. He therefore gave the specific epithet interstans, derived from the Latin words inter meaning "between" and stans "standing".Two subspecies are recognized in the Australian Plant Census:

Eremophila interstans (S.Moore) Diels subsp. interstans which is a shrub or small tree with leaves spreading at an angle to the branches, and cream-coloured flowers appearing between August and early October;
Eremophila interstans subsp. virgata (W.Fitzg.) Chinnock which is a broom-shaped shrub with leaves often held against the branches by resin, and white flowers appearing between October and December.(Subspecies virgata was originally described by William Vincent Fitzgerald as Eremophila virgata.)
